            <!-- Agadir History & Culture Section -->
            <div class="tour-description">
                <h2>Understanding Agadir's Unique History and Culture</h2>
                <p>Our <strong>Agadir city tour</strong> provides deep insights into what makes this city so unique among Moroccan destinations:</p>
                
                <h3 style="font-size: 1.4rem; margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 12px; color: #1F2937;">üìñ The 1960 Earthquake Story</h3>
                <p>On February 29, 1960, at 11:40 PM, a devastating magnitude 5.7 earthquake struck Agadir. In just 15 seconds, 90% of the city was destroyed and 15,000 people (one-third of the population) perished. The old city was buried and abandoned for safety reasons. Morocco's King Mohammed V declared "If destiny has decreed that Agadir be destroyed, its reconstruction depends on our faith and will." The city was rebuilt from scratch just south of the ruins, becoming a model of modern urban planning with wide streets designed for quick evacuation, earthquake-resistant buildings, and no structures over 4 stories in the center. Your <strong>Agadir sightseeing tour</strong> brings this dramatic history to life through personal stories and historical photos.</p>

                <h3 style="font-size: 1.4rem; margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 12px; color: #1F2937;">üèõÔ∏è The Kasbah - Memorial of Old Agadir</h3>
                <p>The <strong>Agadir Kasbah and Medina visit</strong> is emotional and inspiring. The hilltop fortress, built in 1572, partially survived because of its elevated location. Today's ruins serve as a memorial to those who perished and a symbol of the city's resilience. The entrance gate has been restored with the inscription "Fear God and honor the King" still visible. From the Kasbah, you see the entire new city spread below - a phoenix risen from tragedy. Your guide shares personal or family stories about the earthquake, making history tangible and moving.</p>

                <h3 style="font-size: 1.4rem; margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 12px; color: #1F2937;">üõçÔ∏è Souk El Had - Authentic Local Life</h3>
                <p>The <strong>city tour Agadir half day</strong> includes extensive time at Souk El Had, giving you authentic cultural immersion. This isn't a tourist market - it's where locals shop daily! You'll see Moroccan family life in action, learn about traditional spices and ingredients, discover handmade crafts, and practice the art of bargaining. The market has 6,000 vendors and opens every day except Monday. Our guides know the best stalls for quality argan oil, saffron, traditional slippers (babouches), and Berber carpets. It's shopping, cultural education, and people-watching all in one!</p>

                <h3 style="font-size: 1.4rem; margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 12px; color: #1F2937;">üèñÔ∏è Modern Agadir - Morocco's Premier Beach Resort</h3>
                <p>See how Agadir transformed from tragedy to triumph. The <strong>Agadir city tour</strong> shows you the modern city's impressive development - luxury marina, 10km beach promenade, world-class hotels, and thriving tourism industry. Agadir now welcomes over 3 million visitors annually and has become Morocco's most popular beach destination. The city balances modernity with tradition, offering both European-style comfort and authentic Moroccan culture. Your tour explains this successful rebirth and positions you to enjoy all Agadir offers.</p>

                <h3 style="font-size: 1.4rem; margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 12px; color: #1F2937;">üì∏ Photo Opportunities Throughout the Tour</h3>
                <p>This <strong>Agadir sightseeing tour</strong> provides amazing photo opportunities at every stop: panoramic city views from the Kasbah, colorful spice pyramids at the souk, traditional architecture in New Medina, luxury yachts at the marina, and sweeping beach vistas along the Corniche. Your guide knows all the best angles and spots, ensuring you capture memories to share. The afternoon tour offers spectacular golden hour lighting for photography enthusiasts!</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Planning Your City Tour Section -->
            <div class="tour-description">
                <h2>Planning Your Agadir City Tour</h2>
                
                <h3 style="font-size: 1.4rem; margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 12px; color: #1F2937;">When Should I Take the City Tour?</h3>
                <p>We highly recommend taking the <strong>Agadir city tour</strong> on your first or second day in Agadir! Here's why:</p>
                <ul style="margin-left: 25px; color: #6B7280; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 20px;">
                    <li><strong>Perfect Orientation:</strong> Understand the city layout, where everything is, and how to navigate</li>
                    <li><strong>Historical Context:</strong> Learn the earthquake story that explains why Agadir looks different from other Moroccan cities</li>
                    <li><strong>Local Recommendations:</strong> Your guide shares the best restaurants, beaches, and activities for your stay</li>
                    <li><strong>Market Knowledge:</strong> Learn bargaining skills at Souk El Had for future shopping</li>
                    <li><strong>Plan Rest of Trip:</strong> After the tour, you'll know exactly what you want to explore further</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="color: #6B7280; line-height: 1.8; margin-left: 25px;"><strong>Morning Tour (9 AM):</strong> Finishes by 1 PM - afternoon free for beach or activities. Cooler temperatures.</p>
                <p style="color: #6B7280; line-height: 1.8; margin-left: 25px;"><strong>Afternoon Tour (2 PM):</strong> Finishes by 6 PM - catches beautiful sunset from Kasbah. Great for photography!</p>

                <h3 style="font-size: 1.4rem; margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 12px; color: #1F2937;">What Makes Agadir Different from Other Moroccan Cities?</h3>
                <p>Unlike ancient cities like Marrakech or Fez, Agadir is relatively young (rebuilt in 1960s). The city features wide, modern streets, earthquake-resistant architecture, organized urban planning, and a distinctly relaxed beach-town atmosphere. There's no ancient medina maze to get lost in - Agadir is easy to navigate. Our <strong>Agadir sightseeing tour</strong> helps you understand and appreciate these unique characteristics that some visitors initially find surprising.</p>

                <h3 style="font-size: 1.4rem; margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 12px; color: #1F2937;">Why Book a Guided City Tour?</h3>
                <p>While Agadir is easy to explore independently, a <strong>guided city tour Agadir half day</strong> offers substantial value:</p>
                <ul style="margin-left: 25px; color: #6B7280; line-height: 1.8;">
                    <li><strong>Historical storytelling:</strong> The earthquake story and rebirth explained by locals who lived it</li>
                    <li><strong>Navigate efficiently:</strong> See all major sites in 4 hours vs. days of wandering</li>
                    <li><strong>Market insider knowledge:</strong> Bargaining tips, best stalls, fair prices at Souk El Had</li>
                    <li><strong>Hidden gems:</strong> Discover spots tourists miss - local favorite cafes, photo spots, shortcuts</li>
                    <li><strong>Cultural context:</strong> Understand Moroccan customs, etiquette, and traditions</li>
                    <li><strong>Practical information:</strong> Best beaches, restaurants, activities, safety tips</li>
                    <li><strong>No stress:</strong> Hotel pickup, organized schedule, all logistics handled</li>
                    <li><strong>Ask questions:</strong> Small groups mean time for your specific questions and interests</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

